dashboardItems.text:
*SERVICE AVAILABILITY*
Provides information about the availability, accessibility, follow-up evaluations and delivery of hearing technologies to persons with hearing loss. Poor communication among individuals with hearing loss may undermine many health outcomes, including learning and language process, patient satisfaction, adherence to treatment, utilization of health services, healthy behaviour education and medical costs. Hearing aids have been shown to decrease communication barriers and the consequences of hearing loss for people with disabilities. Therefore, it is crucial to provide access to hearing technologies for people with hearing loss. Timely follow-up is an important step in treatment and in improving the quality services provided to individuals. This information can be used for planning at service and subnational/national levels and for hearing loss prevention planning.

*SERVICE UTILIZATION*
Provides important information about service utilization. In short-term, this information can be used for service planning (allocate resources effectively, identify problems and needs, among others) and in the long-term allows to identify epidemiological trends that can affect service utilization and service delivery and planning for hearing loss prevention.

*SERVICE ACCESSIBILITY*
Provides information about possible existent barriers or insufficient provision of services to meet demand. Timely ear surgeries (depending on the condition) can be crucial to maintain hearing and balance functions, while preventing and controlling further dangerous health conditions. Excessive waiting time (from referral for surgery to the surgery itself) can be a sign of inefficiencies in the healthcare system. This information can be used for service planning to allocate resources effectively, identify problems and needs, among others.

*NEWBORN SCREENING COVERAGE*
Provides information about the ratio of newborns born at the facility and screened for hearing loss prior to discharge. In short-term, this information can be used for monitoring newborn hearing screening at facility and subnational/national levels and in the long-term can be used as an assessment for the Universal Newborn Hearing Screening coverage. Screening in newborns and/or infants is the first step towards better identification, and early intervention for hearing loss or other ear related issues. Without hearing screening, newborns/infants with hearing loss are typically identified with an established language delay. By early detection of hearing loss, a child can get the timely and necessary rehabilitation for their speech, language, learning, social and emotional development

dashboardItems.text:
*NEWBORN SCREENING COVERAGE*
Provides information about the ratio of newborns screened for congenital and neonatal eye conditions and about the ratio of eligible preterm infants receiving retinopathy of prematurity screening (eligibility for screening, that is birthweight and gestational age with or without additional sickness criteria, determined by local guidelines). Eye screening in newborns, preferably within 72 hours of birth, is the first step towards better identification, and early intervention of congenital and neonatal eye conditions and provides an opportunity to prevent visual impairment and blindness. Additionally, due to an increase in the number of preterm births, and survival of premature infants, retinopathy of prematurity has become a leading cause of childhood blindness in many middle-income countries. Systematic retinal screening of eligible, preterm, low birth weight infants, using local, evidence-based screening criteria followed by urgent treatment of infants developing the vision-threatening signs of retinopathy of prematurity allows to reduce the risk of vision impairment or blindness. In short-term, this information can be used for service planning and in the long-term can be used as an assessment of the coverage of specific eye care services.

*DIABET RETINOPATHY SCREENING COVERAGE*
Provides information about the coverage provided by the facility and the capacity of the facility to meet demand and can be used for service planning (improving coverage). Systematic eye screening for early detection of diabetic retinopathy in people with diabetes, and referral where indicated, is recommended to ensure early detection and timely treatment to avoid vision impairment caused by diabetic retinopathy. The recommended interval between screening varies according to country’s specific guidelines; most commonly annual and biennial screening is recommended.

*CATARACT SURGERY*
Provides information on timely access of population in need of cataract surgery, possible existent barriers in accessing cataract surgery or insufficient provision of services to meet demand and about the quality of the cataract surgery services. Timely delivery of cataract surgery is critical to maintain visual function and avoid visual impairment or blindness. Excessive waiting times (from referral for surgery to the surgery itself) may be symptoms of inefficiencies in the healthcare system and should be reduced as the condition may deteriorate. Inadequate provision of cataract surgical services is likely to be reflected in a greater proportion of people with very poor preoperative visual acuity. The proportion of people who are blind or have severe vision impairment before cataract surgery allows the monitoring of local progress towards the elimination of vision impairment from cataract. The cataract surgery visual outcome allows to identify the main causes of a possible poor outcome improving future results such as improve case selection; improve quality of surgery and avoid surgical complications; improve operative and/or post-operative correction of refractive error; reduce postoperative complications, among others. This information should be used for service planning (identify problems and needs, improve referral systems, among others).

*SERVICE UTILISATION*
Provides important information about service utilization disaggregated by the different age groups and different eye conditions. In short-term and medium-term, this information can be used for service planning (allocate resources effectively, identify problems and needs, among others) and in the long-term allows to identify epidemiological trends that can affect service utilization and service delivery, allowing to plan for vision impairment and blindness prevention.

dashboardItems.text:
*EYE CARE WORKFORCE DENSITY AND DISTRIBUTION*
The dashboard provides basic information about the availability of the human resources needed for essential eye care services provision. The different profiles and skills of the workforce available in the facilities, allows to indirectly assess the quality of the eye care service delivery system. This information can be used at facility level, for service planning, and at subnational and national levels to identify shortages, allocate resources effectively and better distribute the workforce across health facilities or programmes to meet the population needs.

*HEARING WORKFORCE DENSITY AND DISTRIBUTION*
The dashboard provides basic information about the availability of the human resources needed for essential ear and hearing care services provision. The different profiles and skills of the workforce available in the facilities, allows to indirectly assess the quality of the ear and hearing care service delivery system. This information can be used at facility level, for service planning, and at subnational and national levels to identify shortages, allocate resources effectively and better distribute the workforce across health facilities or programmes to meet the population needs.

Chronic NSOM refers to an ear condition is synonymous with otitis media with effusion (OME).
